{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17626788","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17626788"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:44:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:44:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17098"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17098","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17098"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0,0.75,0.05,0.2]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9788"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76977"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9788","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9788"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17098"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62482"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5108"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22966"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23181"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76977","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76977"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EPropylthiouracil is an antithyroid medication used in the management of hyperthyroidism.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of action of propylthiouracil?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reduces thyroid gland blood flow","Blocks thyroid hormone release from thyroid gland","Inhibits thyroid peroxidase enzyme","Prevents thyroid-stimulating hormone secretion","Competes with iodine uptake at sodium-iodide symporter"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary mechanism of action of propylthiouracil is \u003Cstrong\u003Einhibition of thyroid peroxidase enzyme\u003C/strong\u003E. This enzyme is essential for the iodination of tyrosine residues and coupling reactions required for thyroid hormone synthesis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReducing thyroid gland blood flow\u003C/strong\u003E: propylthiouracil does not have significant effects on thyroid vasculature or blood flow.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocking thyroid hormone release\u003C/strong\u003E: propylthiouracil prevents new hormone synthesis rather than interfering with the release of stored hormones.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPreventing thyroid-stimulating hormone secretion\u003C/strong\u003E: propylthiouracil acts directly on the thyroid gland and does not affect pituitary hormone secretion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECompeting with iodine uptake\u003C/strong\u003E describes the mechanism of perchlorate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPropylthiouracil has an additional unique property of inhibiting the peripheral conversion of thyroxine (T4) to the more active triiodothyronine (T3), making it useful in thyroid storm and during the first trimester of pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Propylthiouracil inhibits thyroid peroxidase enzyme, reducing thyroid hormone synthesis.","Propylthiouracil also inhibits peripheral conversion of thyroxine (T4) to triiodothyronine (T3).","Propylthiouracil is used to treat hyperthyroidism, particularly in the first trimester of pregnancy."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62482"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17098"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62482","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62482"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-05T21:12:04+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T21:12:29+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9788"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76977"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4929","links":